🎬 VIDEO 1: Inheritance
🎤 Script

Inheritance in Java is a concept where one class can acquire the properties and methods of another class.

It helps us reuse code and avoid duplication.

The class that is inherited from is called the parent class, and the class that inherits is called the child class.

For example, if we have a class Animal, and a class Lion, Lion can inherit from Animal.

Benefits of inheritance include code reusability, cleaner structure, and easier maintenance.

There are different types of inheritance:

Single inheritance – one class inherits from one parent.
Multilevel inheritance – a class inherits from a class that already inherited from another class.
Hierarchical inheritance – multiple classes inherit from the same parent.

Java does not support multiple inheritance with classes to avoid ambiguity, but it supports it using interfaces.

🎬 VIDEO 2: Overloading
🎤 Script

Method overloading means having multiple methods with the same name but different parameters.

It is achieved by changing the number of parameters or the type of parameters.

For example, we can have:
add(int a, int b) and add(int a, int b, int c)

Both methods have the same name but different parameter lists.

Overloading happens at compile time, so it is also called compile-time polymorphism.

We can overload methods and constructors.

But we cannot overload methods only by changing the return type.

So method name must be same, but parameters must be different.

🎬 VIDEO 3: Overriding
🎤 Script

Method overriding happens when a child class provides its own implementation of a method that already exists in the parent class.

This is achieved using inheritance.

For example, if Animal has a method makeSound(), the Lion class can override it to print “Roar”.

Overriding happens at runtime, so it is called runtime polymorphism.

The method name, parameters, and return type must be the same.

We cannot override static methods or final methods.

Also, access level cannot be more restrictive than the parent method.

Overriding allows different classes to behave differently using the same method name.